</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Introduction</P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"SIZE=2></B>

<P>Statistics is a field of study concerned with collecting, summarizing and describing data and also with drawing conclusions based on the analysis of data.</P>

<P>Study Lesson 1-51 <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 51 a~?"> section a</a> for an introduction to Statistics. Also  read pages 1–2 of your lecture notes 
to familiarise yourself with some of the terminology used in statistics.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Frequency Distributions</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"SIZE=2>
<P>The aim of descriptive statistics is to summarize data in a form that allows interpretation and analysis.   A useful technique is to list the distinct values in the collection together with the number of times, or frequency, each value occurs.   Organizing data in this manner produces a <B>frequency distribution</B>.   Frequency distributions are introduced in <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 52 c 0~?">1-52 section c</a>.   Try <a href="launch.htm#q0546">q0546</a>.</P>

<P>Now read through frequency distributions in the lecture notes pages 3-6.</P>

<P>The frequency distributions described above are useful when the number of possible values of the variable is not too large (10 or less).   If the number of possible values is large, the frequency distribution will not summarize the data to any great extent, because it will consist of a lengthy table, in which many values of the variable have a low or zero frequency.</P>

<P>When the number of possible values of the variable is large a better description of the data is provided by the so-called <B>grouped frequency</B> <B>distribution</B>.   Find out from pages 7-9 of your lecture notes.   </P>

<P>Now try <a href="launch.htm#q0768">q0768</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0769">q0769</a>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Relative Frequency and Cumulative Frequency</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"SIZE=2>
<P>Now consider <B>Relative Frequency</B> and  <B>Cumulative Frequency</B> Distributions.   Work through <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 55 a~?">1-55 section a</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 55 b 0~?">section b</a> and  <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 55 d 0~?">section d</a>.   Try <a href="launch.htm#q0554">q0554</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0555">q0555</a>.   Find more information in your lecture notes pages 10-11.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Graphical Representations</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>For an introduction to methods of representing data in graphical form, work through Lesson 1-51
<a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 51 b 0~?">section b</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 51 c 0~?">section c</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 51 d 0~?">section d</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 51 e~?">section e</a>.  Try TAS questions <a href="launch.htm#q0540">q0540</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0541">q0541</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0542">q0542</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0543">q0543</a>.</P>

<P>Now study Lesson 1-55 <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 55 e 0~?">section e</a>, which describes the <B>Dot Plot</B>. The dot plot is a useful graphical method of presenting the frequency distribution of a discrete quantitative variable.</P>

<P>Read pages 12-19 in your lecture notes for details on other helpful charts and plots.</P>

